eval_results.model_output: The decomposing bodies of four alleged terrorists who carried out a massacre at a Kenyan university were paraded in front of a large crowd at a primary school today. The authorities drove the naked, bloated corpses of the four men around the town in a pickup truck from the mortuary to Garissa Primary School. The attack at Garissa University College on Thursday left 148 people dead, with the gunmen shooting and beheading those who could not recite the Koran. Four other survivors from the massacre were found yesterday. Kenya's interior minister said the four terrorist gunmen had strapped themselves with explosives and when officers shot at them, they exploded 'like bombs' and shrapnel injured officers. Five suspects have been detained, including three Kenyans of Somali origin and two Tanzanians. The interior ministry said the three suspects arrested at the border had coordinated the attack. The militants said the barbaric attack was in retaliation for killings carried out by Kenyan troops fighting the rebels in Somalia. Kenya's President Uhuru Kenyatta said those behind the attack were 'deeply embedded' in Kenya and called on Kenyan Muslims to help prevent radicalization.</s><s>
